You are debugging a production issue where a high-throughput payment processing service experiences intermittent data races and duplicate payment processing. A custom thread-safe collection uses lock striping based on key identity hashes to ensure exclusive access per account. Here is the class:

java
@Component
public class AccountLockRegistry {
    private final Lock[] locks = new Lock[256];

    public AccountLockRegistry() {
        for (int i = 0; i < locks.length; i++) {
            locks[i] = new ReentrantLock();
        }
    }

    public void executeLocked(Account account, Runnable action) {
        int stripe = Math.abs(System.identityHashCode(account) % locks.length);
        Lock lock = locks[stripe];
        lock.lock();
        try {
            action.run();
        } finally {
            lock.unlock();
        }
    }
}


In this system, `Account` objects are JPA entities loaded via a Spring Boot / Spring Data JPA layer. During heavy concurrent load, multiple threads are observed executing the supposedly locked block for the exact same database record simultaneously.

You are debugging a production memory leak that degrades performance in a microservice. A custom metadata cache was implemented using `WeakHashMap` to allow entries to be automatically evicted when keys are no longer referenced elsewhere. Here is the implementation:

java
public class CustomMetadataCache {
    private final Map<UserSession, SessionMetadata> cache = new WeakHashMap<>();

    public void cacheMetadata(UserSession session, String role, String token) {
        SessionMetadata metadata = new SessionMetadata(session, role, token);
        cache.put(session, metadata);
    }

    private static class SessionMetadata {
        private final UserSession session; 
        private final String role;
        private final String token;

        public SessionMetadata(UserSession session, String role, String token) {
            this.session = session;
            this.role = role;
            this.token = token;
        }
    }
}


Even when external references to `UserSession` objects go out of scope, heap analysis shows that none of the map entries are ever garbage collected.

You are debugging a production issue in a Spring Boot application where users occasionally see sensitive information belonging to other users. You pinpoint the issue to a custom collection used to accumulate auditing events during the lifecycle of an HTTP request within a Spring `@Transactional` service:

java
@Service
public class AuditService {
    private static final ThreadLocal<List<AuditEvent>> auditBuffer = 
        ThreadLocal.withInitial(ArrayList::new);

    @Transactional
    public void processAction(String userId, String action) {
        auditBuffer.get().add(new AuditEvent(userId, action));
        // execute business logic and database updates
        flushAuditLogs();
    }

    private void flushAuditLogs() {
        List<AuditEvent> events = auditBuffer.get();
        if (events.size() >= 5) {
            saveToDatabase(events);
            auditBuffer.get().clear(); 
        }
    }
}


The application runs on an embedded Tomcat container with a default thread pool of 200. During periods of low traffic, users report that audit events from User A are occasionally appended to the list of User B.
